                        </a></div></div><ol class="sense_single" htag="ol"><li class="sense" id="ablutions_sng_1" hclass="sense" htag="li"><span class="sensetop" hclass="sensetop" htag="span"><span class="def" hclass="def" htag="span">the act of washing yourself</span></span><div class="collapse" hclass="collapse" htag="div"><span class="unbox" unbox="wordorigin" id="ablutions_unbox_1"><span class="box_title">Word Origin</span><span class="body"><span class="p">late Middle English: from Latin <span class="ei">ablutio(n-)</span>, from <span class="ei">abluere</span>, from <span class="ei">ab-</span> ‘away’ + <span class="ei">luere</span> ‘wash’. The original use was as a term in chemistry and alchemy meaning ‘purification by using liquids’, hence ‘purification of the body by washing’ (mid 16th cent.).</span></span></span></div>    <div id="ring-links-box">
